00:00:23.910 --> 00:00:25.470
Family Gallery.

00:00:25.470 --> 00:00:30.450
Now Wendy Jacob is a
widely admired artist

00:00:30.450 --> 00:00:31.770
who bridges many practices.

00:00:31.770 --> 00:00:34.360
Among them, the practices
of architecture,

00:00:34.360 --> 00:00:38.730
sculpture, design, invention.

00:00:38.730 --> 00:00:41.430
She was based in
Chicago for many years

00:00:41.430 --> 00:00:46.064
where she received her MFA from
the Art Institute of Chicago,

00:00:46.064 --> 00:00:48.480
and where she was a founding
member of the art collective,

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:52.230
Haha, that was
formed there in 1988,

00:00:52.230 --> 00:00:54.875
and worked together
for some two decades.

00:00:54.875 --> 00:00:58.050
Haha is widely acclaimed for
developing an art practice that

00:00:58.050 --> 00:01:01.740
really pushed at many of the
boundaries of what art could be

00:01:01.740 --> 00:01:04.530
and who had access to it.

00:01:04.530 --> 00:01:07.560
It's many projects, which
included all kinds of community

00:01:07.560 --> 00:01:11.400
based projects, sculptural
installations, video work,

00:01:11.400 --> 00:01:15.030
and so forth, tended in
their words, to be ephemeral.

00:01:15.030 --> 00:01:17.190
Closely interwoven with
the times and places

00:01:17.190 --> 00:01:18.900
where they were
shown and addressed

00:01:18.900 --> 00:01:21.660
the particulars of living
in it locally and centrally

00:01:21.660 --> 00:01:24.030
embedded situation.

00:01:24.030 --> 00:01:26.370
Now in addition to
her work with Haha,

00:01:26.370 --> 00:01:29.040
Jacob also developed her
own artistic projects

00:01:29.040 --> 00:01:32.520
that explored among other
things, the relationships

00:01:32.520 --> 00:01:36.510
between architecture and
perceptual experience.

00:01:36.510 --> 00:01:38.160
The interface
between architecture

00:01:38.160 --> 00:01:40.470
and the bodies of the
peoples and animals

00:01:40.470 --> 00:01:42.720
inhabiting the
built environment.

00:01:42.720 --> 00:01:44.880
And in this regard,
Jacob has been

00:01:44.880 --> 00:01:47.400
the consummate
collaborator who's

00:01:47.400 --> 00:01:49.920
worked in a collective
with other artists.

00:01:49.920 --> 00:01:54.990
But also with architects,
engineers, researchers

00:01:54.990 --> 00:01:56.640
in various fields
over the years,

00:01:56.640 --> 00:02:01.080
really yielding a long list of
solo exhibitions, publications,

00:02:01.080 --> 00:02:04.710
and residencies, nationally
and internationally, too

00:02:04.710 --> 00:02:06.210
numerous to enumerate here.

00:02:06.210 --> 00:02:08.310
Although I should be
remiss not to mention

00:02:08.310 --> 00:02:11.039
that she was formerly a fellow
at the Radcliffe institute

00:02:11.039 --> 00:02:13.350
in the year 2005.

00:02:13.350 --> 00:02:15.360
One of her more
well-known collaborations

00:02:15.360 --> 00:02:18.210
was with Temple Grandin,
the animal scientist who

00:02:18.210 --> 00:02:22.620
has written widely on autism,
and catalyzed by conversations

00:02:22.620 --> 00:02:25.650
with Grandin, Jacob
developed the squeeze chair,

00:02:25.650 --> 00:02:29.940
which consists of a
series of chairs really,

00:02:29.940 --> 00:02:33.960
with arms that inflate to
hold the sitter in a firm hug.

00:02:33.960 --> 00:02:36.300
It takes its cue from the
fact that many with autism

00:02:36.300 --> 00:02:40.680
are especially receptive to the
calming effects of pressure.

00:02:40.680 --> 00:02:43.350
In 2006, Jacob founded
the autism studio

00:02:43.350 --> 00:02:46.230
at MIT, a multi-disciplinary
studio that

00:02:46.230 --> 00:02:49.350
aims to explore perceptual
features afforded

00:02:49.350 --> 00:02:51.900
by the broad range of
autistic experience

00:02:51.900 --> 00:02:54.240
and to create objects
and spaces and events

00:02:54.240 --> 00:02:57.630
that really resonated
with these experiences.

00:02:57.630 --> 00:03:00.180
More recently, over
the past two years,

00:03:00.180 --> 00:03:02.970
Jacob has worked with the
Cherry Road Resource Center

00:03:02.970 --> 00:03:05.640
for the Disabled in
Scotland to understand,

00:03:05.640 --> 00:03:08.640
among other things, the nature
of the tactility of sound

00:03:08.640 --> 00:03:10.960
for the hearing impaired.

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:13.520
Now the exhibition
that opens today, Calm.

00:03:13.520 --> 00:03:16.080
Smoke Rises Vertically,
really extends

00:03:16.080 --> 00:03:17.970
in new ways, the
vectors of inquiry

00:03:17.970 --> 00:03:20.460
that Jacob has been
pursuing over the years.

00:03:20.460 --> 00:03:22.350
Most notably, here
interest in expanding

00:03:22.350 --> 00:03:25.540
the sensory dimensions of art.

00:03:25.540 --> 00:03:28.290
In the Johnson-Kulakundis
Gallery,

00:03:28.290 --> 00:03:30.960
10 architectural models are
displayed in combination

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:33.140
with meteorological
information, which

00:03:33.140 --> 00:03:35.220
is played through the
walls of the gallery.

00:03:35.220 --> 00:03:37.410
And both the models
and the weather

00:03:37.410 --> 00:03:39.780
reports, convey
empirical knowledge that,

00:03:39.780 --> 00:03:42.720
by calibrating a
verbal description

00:03:42.720 --> 00:03:45.120
to sensory experience.

00:03:45.120 --> 00:03:48.000
The architectural models
displayed in the gallery

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:50.600
are on loan from the
Perkins School for the Blind

00:03:50.600 --> 00:03:53.310
and the Ohio State
School for the Blind.

00:03:53.310 --> 00:03:55.020
They have an
interesting history.

00:03:55.020 --> 00:03:59.730
They were created between
the years 1935 in 1943,

00:03:59.730 --> 00:04:02.490
under the auspices of the
WPA, the Works Progress

00:04:02.490 --> 00:04:05.580
Administration, which
mobilized many craftsmen

00:04:05.580 --> 00:04:08.250
and specialists to create
tactile models for.

00:04:08.250 --> 00:04:10.017
blind students.

00:04:10.017 --> 00:04:11.850
The models were intended
to convey knowledge

00:04:11.850 --> 00:04:15.150
about architecture through
touch, allowing blind students

00:04:15.150 --> 00:04:18.180
to see them for the first time.

00:04:18.180 --> 00:04:21.390
The weather reports which are
conveyed through the walls,

00:04:21.390 --> 00:04:26.190
include a live streaming of the
weather broadcast of the NOAA.

00:04:26.190 --> 00:04:30.720
Also live sounds from outdoors
and a reading of the Beaufort

00:04:30.720 --> 00:04:32.420
Wind Scale.

00:04:32.420 --> 00:04:34.110
The Beaufort Wind
Scale is a scale

00:04:34.110 --> 00:04:36.240
that was developed in
the early 19th century

00:04:36.240 --> 00:04:40.800
to match a defined set
of verbal descriptions

00:04:40.800 --> 00:04:45.000
to approximate wind speeds, with
the practical aim of allowing

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:47.400
users to, on land
or sea, to quantify

00:04:47.400 --> 00:04:49.710
the observable
conditions around them.

00:04:49.710 --> 00:04:52.920
And so for example, a 4
on the Beaufort Scale,

00:04:52.920 --> 00:04:54.570
which is a brisk
breeze is indicated

00:04:54.570 --> 00:04:59.220
by the phrase small trees
and leaf begin to sway.

00:04:59.220 --> 00:05:01.140
So the title of the
exhibition Calm.

00:05:01.140 --> 00:05:03.810
Smoke Rises Vertically
describes a wind speed

00:05:03.810 --> 00:05:05.800
of less than one knot.

00:05:05.800 --> 00:05:08.520
Now the exhibition highlights
in a wonderful way,

00:05:08.520 --> 00:05:11.800
the correspondences between
the tactile models and weather

00:05:11.800 --> 00:05:14.710
reports, in order to
underscore the ways in which

00:05:14.710 --> 00:05:17.830
perceptual experiences
through different senses

00:05:17.830 --> 00:05:21.490
reinforce and
transform one another.

00:05:21.490 --> 00:05:24.700
In the models, touching
is synonymous with seeing.

00:05:24.700 --> 00:05:27.430
Whereas in the weather
reports, the invisible,

00:05:27.430 --> 00:05:30.364
the wind is rendered
comprehensible.

00:05:30.364 --> 00:05:31.780
And by playing the
weather reports

00:05:31.780 --> 00:05:34.600
through the walls of the
gallery, Jacob in essence,

00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:36.670
transforms the gallery
walls themselves,

00:05:36.670 --> 00:05:39.530
into large surfaces of sound.

00:05:39.530 --> 00:05:42.760
Speakers of sound
thus generating

00:05:42.760 --> 00:05:46.900
an equivalence again
between its tactility,

00:05:46.900 --> 00:05:49.150
and that of the models.

00:05:49.150 --> 00:05:53.500
